Up for sale we have a 1969 Chevy Chevelle SS 396.  This is a real Super Sport with a certificate of Authenticity from Jerry MacNeish showing it to be a L78 396/375HP SS Chevelle that has the L89 Aluminum Heads upgrade.  In the paragraphs to follow we will give a brief description of the exterior, interior, and heartbeat of the Chevy, but first we would like to tell you a little about us.

Smoky Mountain Traders is a classic car dealer in east Tennessee. We are family owned, operated, and own our entire inventory, no consignments, and only deal in muscle cars and vintage auto. You can count on us to have 50 to 60 cars at all times. We don't have a big show room that our customers would otherwise pay for. So, that's how we can sell for less than other dealers. To contact us for more information, pictures, or any questions call our office at (865)988-8088 or visit our SmokyMountainTraders website.

We will start off with the exterior of the Chevelle.  You can see the time that was spent to ensure a good fit of all the panels.  All the stainless looks good as well as the glass.  They replaced all the weather stripping and seals as well.  When you look at the chrome, the bumpers look new as well as other trim.  This Chevelle is painted in the factory Tuxedo Black that is slick with a deep rich shine that shows very well. The final exterior touch is the set of factory SS wheels with a set of Goodyear Red Line tires.

Next, we will take a look at the interior of the Super Sport.  On the inside it's all done in black that flows with the exterior perfectly.  It has the bucket seats and console with the correct shifter.  Also it has the gauge pack dash with factory tach.  The radio is the Factory AM/FM with a remote 8track in the glove box.

Finally, we will take a look at the heartbeat of the Chevy.  Under the hood it has an L78 396/375HP Big Block with the L89 (GM ALUMINUN HEADS) upgrade.  The engine is dressed with the stock aluminum intake and Holley Carb.  It has the chrome valve covers along with a chrome breather.  Also it retain the stock manifolds with 2 ½'' Exhaust with Flow Master Mufflers.  This Chevelle retains the smog pump and a stock looking engine compartment.  The engine is mated to a Muncie 4 Speed and a 12 Bolt Rear End with 4.10 Gears.  This Chevelle has power steering and power front disc brakes.  The floors and frame appear super solid with no signs of rust or rot.

We will start off with the exterior of the Chevelle.  It's straight down the sides and covered in the Frost White base/clear that has been buffed and polished to a slick finish.  This '66 has the custom Cowl Hood along with dual mirrors.  All the chrome and stainless is in great condition.  Most of it appears to have been replaced but is showing some light aging.  All the glass is very nice and the weather stripping around the doors and trunk looks new.  To complete the killer look it has 16x10 rear wheels with 275/45 tires and 16x8 front wheels with 225/55 tires.

Next, we will move to the interior of the '66.  On the inside, it's done in the Blue and white color combo that complements the exterior perfectly.  The bench seats are done in blue with the white insert and all the padding is in great condition.  The door panels are also done in blue and have been replaced, and the headliner is done in white.  Looking at the dash it's done in blue and features the upgraded gauges that are all working.  The radio has been upgraded and the vintage AC is controlled from the factory location.

Finally, we will get to the heartbeat of the Chevy.  Under the hood is where you are going to fall in love.  With over 550 HP the is one of the most powerful engines GM has ever offered.  The 6.2 Supercharged LSA motor you'll find under the hood of this Chevelle is mated to the Tremec Six Speed and 12 Bolt Posi Rear End.  It's got the cold air breather and it also has an Aluminum Radiator.  Also, it comes with Air Condition, Power Steering and Power Four Wheel Disc Brakes with drilled and slotted Rotors.  When you look under this '66 you'll see front and rear sway bars from Spohn.  Also, the front control arms are Tubular and it has new springs front and rear.  Looking at the floors they have done some work around the tunnel to accommodate the tremec, and the front floor pans have been patched at the front.  The frame all appears solid and in good condition along with the body bushings.

Matching Numbers 428ci engine, Factory 4 speed & Safe-T-Track Rear

Just about any muscle car in the 60s could be ordered with a 4-speed transmission, but rarely was it ordered for a Bonneville. How rare is it? According to PHS documentation, more than 104,000 Bonnevilles (model 262) were made in 1968. Of those, only 7358 were convertibles and just 208 were convertibles with a 428ci engine and 4-speed transmission.
The engine is a matching numbers (WG code) 428ci 375hp engine (Rochester 4 barrel carburetor), original 4speed M code transmission and Safe-T-Track (posi) rear. Its all here!

The rust free body is in excellent condition with no dings or dents. All chrome and trim shine like new with no pitting. Body panels are straight, rust free and all original. It has had a high end repaint in its original color of Meridian Turquoise. The white power top is very clean and has the optional glass rear window. Optional body colored side molding and optional cornering lights add to this cars class and appeal.

The white interior is completely original and looks beautiful. Seats are clean and have no rips or tears. Original AM-FM stereo with front and rear speakers work perfectly. Factory AC and heat work as well. Factory hood tach works perfectly and is a very rare option — most hood tachometers were aftermarket add-ons. Power steering, power brakes, wood steering wheel with tilt. Reclining passenger seat and much more.

On the road, this car is smooth, quiet and refined, as a big Bonneville should be yet, she can move along very quickly in any gear when tested. She starts right up, idles steady and is very responsive when pushed. Stopping is not a problem at any speed. There is no pulling on or off the brakes. The cabin is quiet with no rattles or unwanted noises. Its all you'd want and expect from a big GM cruiser.

Plenty of documentation accompanies this Bonneville, including PHS documentation. Other documentation includes the Original Owners manuals, Owner ID, Warranty info, Original Sales Contract and Build Sheet.

These big muscle car cruisers do not come along very often. This is a real deal matching numbers 428ci engine with the paperwork to back it up. "RARE" is an understatement for this car. Dont think about it too long. Call us now to get a one of a kind classic.

Up for sale we have a 1934 Mercury Pick Up.  Before you pick up the phone and call us we know they didn't make a '34 Mercury Pick Up.  However, if they did we sure hope it would have looked like this.  The truck we have started it's life as a 34 Ford then Ricky Bobby Rod Shop turned into this sweet ride.  This car took the Good Guys Builder Choice award and is an absolute head turner.  In the paragraphs to follow we will give a brief description of the exterior, interior, and driveline of the Mercury, but first we would like to tell you a little about us.

Smoky Mountain Traders is a classic car dealer in east Tennessee. We are family owned, operated, and own our entire inventory, no consignments, and only deal in muscle cars and vintage auto. You can count on us to have 70 to 80 cars at all times. We don't have a big show room that our customers would otherwise pay for. So, that's how we can sell for less than other dealers. To contact us for more information, pictures, or any questions call our office at (865)988-8088 or visit our SmokyMountainTraders website.

We will start off with the exterior of the truck.  They started with a 34 Ford Cab that was chopped 4''.  The frame, Hood and Side Panels are made from flat stock that was worked and rolled to fit.  The side panels had custom inserts to fit around the engine.  For the bed they started with a repop bed that was shortened and has a custom Mercury Tail Gate.  Everything is painted in the Rich Navy Blue that has a deep rich shine and is slick to the touch.  To keep with the old school look the wheels up front are 16x4 from a 40 Ford and the rears are 18x7 custom Circle Racing Wheels with Merc Hub Caps.

Next, we will take a look at the interior of the '34.  The inside is done in Tan Leather with a bench seat.  All the metal dash is painted body color to create the perfect flow from the exterior to the interior.  It has a 40 Ford Insturment panels and steering column with a 15'' 40 Ford Wheel.  The pedals are by Kugel.  This truck also has the tilt out front windshield.

Finally, we will take a look at the drivetrain of the Mercury.  Under the custom hood is a '51 Merc Flat Head V8.  It has Eddie Meyer Heads and Intake with Stromberg 97 Carbs.  The trans is a 3 Speed with Over Drive.  The frame is from a 34 Ford that was sectioned 2 ½''  it was also boxed form the firewall back.  Under the front is a So Cal 4'' Drop Axle with 37 Ford Spindles and wish bone.  Under the back is a 39 Zepher Rear Wish Bone.  When you look under this truck it's every bit as clean as the top.

This is a true one of a kind ride that as we mentioned has Won at Major Shows like Good Guys.  But more than just to look at it she was built to drive. If you're in the market for something fun that's guaranteed to hold its appeal for a very long time, it's hard to go wrong with a lust worthy truck! America's favorite mode of transportation is finally commanding the respect it deserves. And with awesome classics like this clean C10 mixing red carpet looks with everyday drivability, it's not hard to see why. A perfect blend of timeless style and proven mechanicals, this handsome half-ton is a first rate exercise in old school charm and vintage swagger. And if you're looking for a super cool cruiser that can be enjoyed for years to come, it's the classic of your dreams!

As far as styling goes, few vehicles have aged better than late '60s and early '70s Chevrolets. In fact, toeing the line between rock-solid and refined, the Action Line C/K is probably one of the most attractive trucks ever built. Making the best of that model's boxy proportions, this fleetside C10 seals slick, black paint under a glossy clearcoat shell. That sinister 2-stage highlights a laser-straight body, the result of a fresh restoration that wrapped in the Spring of 2015. That clean body's top-notch metalwork is, from the outside of its panels, completely undetectable. And best of all, those panels remain just as GM designed them, with nothing frenched, filled or altered in any major way.

However, there are some cool details that really make this build pop. The reboot began with a black-trimmed grille, which hangs a vivid bowtie and bright halogen headlights above a mirrored bumper and factory parking lamps. Behind that grille, a domed hood leads the eye to fresh glass that's centered between a factory antenna, polished wipers and a small cargo light. At the sides of that glass, the truck's monochromatic, wet-look profile has been shaved of everything but traditional door handles, a simple fuel filler and 1-piece marker lamps. And at the back of that profile, a smoothed tailgate hides a clean Oak bed between trim-free tail lights and a second mirrored bumper.

Gaze in to the truck's body-matched engine bay and you'll find 427 cubic inches of Chevrolet big block! At the top of that storied mill, a Quick Fuel Technology 4-barrel mixes wind supplied by a polished and decaled air filter with fuel that's piped through stainless fluid lines and a mechanical pump. That air/fuel mixture floods a polished Edelbrock intake on the way to iron Chevrolet heads, which hang polished valve covers between a polished breather and Hooker Competition headers. At the back of those heads, an aftermarket HEI distributor sequences spark through loomed Moroso Wire Technologies plug wires. Opposite that distributor, a combination of billet and steel pulleys spin a rebuilt alternator, requisite power steering and a modern AC compressor. In front of those pulleys, a fresh aluminum radiator circulates coolant around a stylized support and shrouded pulley fan. And details like a Lokar throttle linkage, a CPP master cylinder and factory-spec Harrison AC components frame the Chevy Orange engine in a sea of pleasing and functional ancillaries.

With that kind of power on tap, it should come as no surprise that the bottom of this C10 features a host of noteworthy upgrades. Everything starts with a sturdy, factory chassis that was thoroughly powder-coated during the truck's frame-off restoration. Behind the sweet engine, a proven 700R4 4-speed engages a stout, 12-bolt rear end. That fully sorted drivetrain rides on a lowered, factory-spec suspension. Stops are provided by red, power-assisted calipers, which squeeze drilled and slotted rotors at all four corners. Modern power steering provides good feel and great performance. Spent gases float from the aforementioned headers to Mandrel-bent pipes and polished Magnaflow mufflers. Power meets the pavement through Billet Specialties Bonneville Gs, which spin a quartet of 255/55R18 Nitto NT420S. And everything, from this Chevy's stainless fluid lines to its urethane chassis bushings, is fresh, expertly finished and ready for action.

In the '70s, trucks were all about comfort and utility – not DVDs, wireless and navigation systems. That's why it's so refreshing to hop in the cab of this purposeful but nicely appointed half-ton. The star of the show is a houndstooth bench that definitely ups the style quotient. Below that seat, stain-free carpet is stretched tight between fresh sound deadening and stainless-trimmed foot pedals. Above that carpet, petite door panels found chrome door handles behind chrome window cranks. Above those panels, a stainless-trimmed headliner leads a manually operated courtesy lamp. Steering is channeled through a familiar Chevy rally wheel, which spins around a tilting column. And at the front of the cockpit, a stylish dash hangs factory telemetry beside factory air conditioning and a direct-fit stereo.
